WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: IVM

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.000
[Amit Varma]: India was no longer a democratic country.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:34.000
[Amit Varma]: And then we got lucky, we got our democracy back,

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:36.000
[Amit Varma]: and everything came back to normal.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
[Amit Varma]: Well, yes and no.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.000
[Amit Varma]: All that I just said is true, but it's not the whole truth.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Indira Gandhi was a monster, her son Sanjay even more so.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
[Amit Varma]: But the most monstrous thing about the emergency

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
[Amit Varma]: was that our constitution and our laws allowed for it.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Our constitution did not give fundamental rights the protection they deserved,

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:59.000
[Amit Varma]: and our founding fathers, from Nehru to Siddharth Patel to Ambedkar,

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
[Amit Varma]: all felt that the Indian state needed to have

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:08.000
[Amit Varma]: precisely the kind of draconian powers that Indira later used to her own advantage.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
[Amit Varma]: And it isn't only the constitution that was flawed.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Our lawmakers consistently treated us as if we were subjects, not citizens.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
[Amit Varma]: In a manner of speaking, the emergency was no aberration.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:22.000
[Amit Varma]: It was inevitable.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:27.000
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen,

