00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
[Amit Varma]: Gyan, welcome to the scene in the NC. Thank you. Thank you.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Gyan, when I picked up a copy of your book Emergency Chronicles,

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
[Amit Varma]: at first I thought that it's going to be sort of a narrative of what happened during the emergency,

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
[Amit Varma]: like Gumi Kapoor's excellent book a couple of years ago.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.000
[Amit Varma]: But reading it, I was delighted and surprised to find that it's a lot more than that.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:57.000
[Amit Varma]: It actually goes much deeper into all the structural causes of why the emergency was,

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:02.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, not an aberration, but almost inevitable in some senses.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And a key part of your story really happens during the framing of the Indian Constitution,

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:13.000
[Amit Varma]: when there is a lot of turmoil on the streets, and you have the framers who are framing

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
[Amit Varma]: the Constitution in the context of the turmoil outside.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:25.000
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, the background for that is that I came to think about writing about the emergency

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:34.000
[Guest]: when I was in Delhi in 2011. In August, there was a rally for Anna Hazare in Ramlila Maidan,

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:40.000
[Guest]: and I happened to go there. And so I thought, you know, I'll go and see what's going on.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:46.000
[Guest]: And, you know, the place was kind of swarming with young people, and young people of a different kind,

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:51.000
[Guest]: you know, what people call the aspirational class, you know, first generation,

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:56.000
[Guest]: educated people who wanted jobs and opportunities.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
[Guest]: And they were there with a great deal of kind of optimism and hope.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:06.000
[Guest]: And what struck me was first, the predominance of the young people.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:13.000
[Guest]: And the second was a kind of an anti-politics air that, you know, all politicians are crooked,

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
[Guest]: and we need some kind of transparency and escape from this.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:22.000
[Guest]: And that reminded me then of the JP movement. And I said, you know, I've seen this before.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:28.000
[Guest]: And there was this kind of, you know, populist sentiment, which was everywhere.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:34.000
[Guest]: And then I thought of many of the things that were happening in the world around that time,

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:40.000
[Guest]: like Dhariv Square, Occupy. Now, each one has its own particular, you know, context.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:46.000
[Guest]: But what was common to all of them was, again, this kind of anti-political sentiment.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:51.000
[Guest]: So I began to think of the emergency. And I said to myself that, you know,

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:57.000
[Guest]: I knew the kind of literature that had come from the journalists and politicians,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:04.000
[Guest]: but they had sequestered the whole thing into 21 months. And the story was very clear.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:10.000
[Guest]: So you have, you know, Indira Gandhi as the kind of prime culprit.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:18.000
[Guest]: And she is, you know, painted as a person who just wants power.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:28.000
[Guest]: And on the other side, you have the saintly, frail, JP, you know, figure of innocence and transparency.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:33.000
[Guest]: So corrupt and so on. I didn't think that, you know, story was altogether untrue,

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:40.000
[Guest]: but it was so simplified that I thought I have to kind of look into its history.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:46.000
[Guest]: So that's when I began digging. And, you know, the first thing that occurred to me was that,

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:51.000
[Guest]: you know, emergency was not illegal. It was in the constitution.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:07:00.000
[Guest]: And then many of the laws that were used, like preventive detention, D.I.R., MISA, all these laws,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
[Guest]: they were on the books that the parliament had passed.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:08.000
[Guest]: So to me, it seemed like, you know, Indira Gandhi didn't drop from the sky,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.000
[Guest]: but emerged in the context of Indian history.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:20.000
[Guest]: So it seemed really logical to go back and, you know, look at the, you know, framing of the constitution.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, just to quote directly from your book, start quote,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:28.000
[Amit Varma]: resistance, riots and violence only strengthened the resolve to bring a strong centralized state.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:34.000
[Amit Varma]: They helped invoke a Hobbesian state of nature, which has typically served to justify the founding of a state

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:39.000
[Amit Varma]: as an inaugural act of extracting unity out of chaos. Stop quote.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And you kind of write about how there was so much violence erupting in so many places that

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:50.000
[Amit Varma]: different founding fathers of the Indian Republic like Patel, like Ambedkar, spoke for quote unquote,

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:55.000
[Amit Varma]: a strong center, you need to hold it together. And there might have been a vision earlier,

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:59.000
[Amit Varma]: like you talk about Nehru's post-national idea of India, which never came to be.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:05.000
[Amit Varma]: And you talk earlier about how there might have been the possibility of a very federal sort of system

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:09.000
[Amit Varma]: where the states have a lot more power, but because of all this violence erupting

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:13.000
[Amit Varma]: and the immediate imperative to keep India as a strong union,

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:18.000
[Amit Varma]: the framers of our constitution ended up giving the state an enormous amount of power.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:23.000
[Guest]: Yeah. You know, when I went back to the framing of the constitution,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:30.000
[Guest]: so I read in one of the places that when the members of the constituent assembly met in Delhi,

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:35.000
[Guest]: they had to get curfew passes. So there was something really bizarre about this,

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:40.000
[Guest]: that here these people are meeting in the constituent assembly and they're talking about something

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:48.000
[Guest]: very kind of rational, like law, and just outside the city, the city is stormed.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:57.000
[Guest]: So I thought that, you know, I have to do some more research into really what the post-war turmoil looked like.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:02.000
[Guest]: And in fact, that's when with another colleague of mine and a student of mine,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:09.000
[Guest]: we did a kind of a conference in Princeton on the post-colonial moment in South and Southeast Asia,

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:16.000
[Guest]: where we looked at across South and Southeast Asia, Indonesia, Burma, India, Pakistan.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
[Guest]: What was the context like? And it seemed like the more I read,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:25.000
[Guest]: and if you also bring Europe into the picture, that across the world,

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:29.000
[Guest]: World War II had a very, very deep impact, not just in terms of killing,

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:35.000
[Guest]: but in terms of the deep penetration of the state into society.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:39.000
[Guest]: So when you are recruiting on that kind of scale to fight a war,

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:43.000
[Guest]: when you're mobilizing resources on that scale for a war,

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:49.000
[Guest]: that really means that society is now much more involved in the affairs of the state.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:56.000
[Guest]: And so in India, too, the state capacity during the war changes enormously,

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:04.000
[Guest]: becomes a much more important entity. So I was reading about this and then I realized from my reading

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:10.000
[Guest]: that after the Second World War, when people come out on the street, there are two things going on.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:18.000
[Guest]: One is after 200 years of British rule, they have a great deal of aspiration, what freedom would bring.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:24.000
[Guest]: And at the same time, they are very conflicting ideas of what that freedom might mean.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
[Guest]: You know, and formation of Pakistan is part of that picture.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:36.000
[Guest]: So in that turmoil, there are so many disparate passions and, you know, conflicts that are in play.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:42.000
[Guest]: And so the lawmakers are writing the constitution against that background.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:48.000
[Guest]: And so the unity of the country is, of course, uppermost in mind.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:54.000
[Guest]: But they're also very aware that people want some dramatic change

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:59.000
[Guest]: and that the state must become an instrument of that change.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:05.000
[Guest]: So, you know, people, political theorists talk about two different models of constitution.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:12.000
[Guest]: The American model in the 18th century was governed by the fact that, you know,

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:20.000
[Guest]: the American leaders distrusted political power and the thought political power leads to corruption.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:26.000
[Guest]: And therefore, they devised a system that was much more federal, full of checks and balances and so on.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:32.000
[Guest]: And then you have the French model where you have revolution, you have coming of the state,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:38.000
[Guest]: and the intent is to destroy the aristocracy and bring about change.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:44.000
[Guest]: And most of the postcolonial countries went for the French model, as did India.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:49.000
[Guest]: So in writing a constitution, they wanted not only a state that would maintain unity,

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:53.000
[Guest]: but also that would be an instrument of social change.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:12:00.000
[Guest]: And certainly Ambedkar was very committed to the idea because he didn't have any faith,

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:08.000
[Guest]: understandably so, in the capacity of society to generate any kind of radical social change.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:13.000
[Guest]: And so for him, it was important that there would be a state governed by law,

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.000
[Guest]: which would be an instrument of that social change.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:21.000
[Guest]: And so that's how we ended up with a very strong centralized state.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:30.000
[Guest]: I mean, in name, they use the term federal, but it's not really a federal system.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:35.000
[Guest]: And I think, you know, you can see the effect of that in what's going on now,

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:44.000
[Guest]: because the state has so much power that you don't even have to formally declare emergency anymore.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:47.000
[Amit Varma]: You can have a silent creeping emergency.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:52.000
[Amit Varma]: One of the terms that kept recurring through your book and was very resonant was passive revolution,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.000
[Amit Varma]: where you talk about how, you know, at independence, we had political transformation,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:01.000
[Amit Varma]: but, you know, and Ambedkar would probably lament this if he was, if he could see this,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:07.000
[Amit Varma]: no social transformation at all. It was almost as if the government is disconnected from the people.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:14.000
[Guest]: Yeah. I mean, the whole idea of passive revolution is a political revolution without social revolution.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
[Guest]: And so it's a revolution at the top.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:24.000
[Guest]: And the idea is that the people at the top would then enact social changes.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:27.000
[Guest]: So the agency remains with the elites.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:32.000
[Guest]: And Ambedkar has that, you know, famous line in 1949, where he says,

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:38.000
[Guest]: we have established political equality, but not social equality.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:44.000
[Guest]: And if this continues, you know, one day, the whole thing will blow up.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:53.000
[Guest]: So and I think, you know, people like Nehru who were committed to social change,

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:59.000
[Guest]: but still thought that that would come about through the action of the leaders,

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:03.000
[Guest]: that we would pass law, land reforms, all of these things that we would do.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:12.000
[Guest]: But Indian democracy put a very high premium on the ability of the leadership

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:20.000
[Guest]: to maintain that kind of high ground and long term outlook.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:25.000
[Guest]: And that is why I think one of the problems of Indian democracy is that, you know,

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:33.000
[Guest]: what if, as it happened, the leadership doesn't measure up to the expectation.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:39.000
[Guest]: And instead of thinking of democracy as a way to institute equality,

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
[Guest]: if they think of democracy as just a game of power,

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:49.000
[Guest]: then you have shrunk the vision of democracy, and then politics becomes just a game of power.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:54.000
[Guest]: And, you know, so I think that was one of the consequences of this passive revolution.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:59.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it's been said that the rules and institutions that you design should be designed,

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:03.000
[Amit Varma]: keeping in mind the need to keep a check on the rulers.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:08.000
[Amit Varma]: So it doesn't matter how bad the person in power is, you could have a mad megalomaniac in power,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
[Amit Varma]: but the rules and institutions should be strong enough to keep them in check.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And instead, what we have, as you pointed out, is partly because of the imperatives of the turmoil that was outside.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:23.000
[Amit Varma]: You almost had the new Indian government taking inspiration from the colonial overlords.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And even the Government of India Act in 1935 was really framed by the colonial powers to keep their subjects in check.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:33.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's very much the spirit that pervaded our constitution makers.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:40.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you have a sentence here, quote, the elite was compelled to rule with a heavy degree of coercion. Stop quote.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And you had Somnath Lahiri, in fact, saying eloquently that many of these fundamental rights have been framed from the point of view of a police constable.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a great line.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:58.000
[Guest]: It's a great line. And, you know, and there's also I mean, I have also a quotation from Ambedkar, where Ambedkar.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:07.000
[Guest]: So there was criticism of the fact that the draft constitution had imported 80 percent of the Government of India Act.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:17.000
[Guest]: And Ambedkar says, I make no apology for the fact that we have imported a large portion of Government of India Act because he thought,

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:23.000
[Guest]: you know, those things were necessary. And of course, in importing that 80 percent,

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:30.000
[Guest]: you imported all the kind of police powers and surveillance powers that the colonial government wanted.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:39.000
[Guest]: And so the Indian state, as it emerges, it emerges with powers that are not very different from the colonial state.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:51.000
[Guest]: I mean, there is one scholar, Sandipto Dasgupta, who's written a very interesting article where he talks about the two sides of Indian constitution making.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:56.000
[Guest]: So it would be untrue to say that nothing changed.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:02.000
[Guest]: You know, so the communists in 1947 said, yeah, that the duty and it was a hoax.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:10.000
[Guest]: And that's not true because something does change. And the mandate is for citizenship.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:17.000
[Guest]: You know, that was a huge thing compared to colonial rule, giving adult suffrage to everyone.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:23.000
[Guest]: And in a way, it's also a radical step when you compare it to, you know,

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:32.000
[Guest]: the writings of great liberal thinkers like John Stuart Mill and so on, who believe that citizenship depended on education.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:37.000
[Guest]: And here we were giving citizenship to mass of illiterate people.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:46.000
[Guest]: So it was a huge radical step. But at the same time, this Dasgupta speaks about the administrative state.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:53.000
[Guest]: And as far as the administrative state was concerned, where, you know, police powers and all those things are involved,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:59.000
[Guest]: the Indian state kind of remained unchanged from the colonial state.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:10.000
[Guest]: And the reason behind that, the power of the administrative state has to go back to, I mean, the way in which the British saw India.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:17.000
[Guest]: And they saw themselves as an island in an ocean of kind of alien people.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:22.000
[Guest]: And they felt that in order to rule such a population, they would need extraordinary power.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:30.000
[Guest]: So it goes back to actually 1818. And you can see that in Rowlatt Act and D.I.R. and all those rules that they had formed.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:42.000
[Guest]: And the Indian state, because they were elites, they also saw themselves as being surrounded by an ocean of illiterate masses

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:49.000
[Guest]: for whom they saw being responsible for their well-being and for their transformation.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:59.000
[Guest]: But still, that vast gulf remained. And that then explained their preference for these administrative powers.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:09.000
[Amit Varma]: So would you say that there's a kind of a paradox here that on the one hand, we've gained freedom and you want all the people of India to be free people?

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:17.000
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, this view of sort of the elites looking at the ocean of chaos around them is also somewhat paternalistic.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:23.000
[Amit Varma]: The same kind of like the civilizing impulse that Macaulay talked about, for example, that these are people and we have to.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And what ends up happening there, therefore, is through the constitution and through the way they rule,

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:38.000
[Amit Varma]: the elites end up imposing a system of values that is imposed from top down and may not really be endorsed by society at large.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's, therefore, in some senses, a kind of liberal paradox where you may try to impose liberal values, but the imposition itself is illiberal.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:55.000
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, because, you know, the elites have a belief in the universality of their views.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:05.000
[Guest]: And, you know, there's a very interesting moment in Nehru's discovery of India, when he is going around the village and, you know, the peasants are saying,

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:14.000
[Guest]: Bharat Mata Ki Jai. And Nehru talks about this and he says, you know, I didn't understand what did they mean? Bharat Mata Ki Jai.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:25.000
[Guest]: Do you mean this soil? So he actually goes, I mean, you know, Nehru is very interesting that he's also very self-aware of his distance from the mass of the people.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:40.000
[Guest]: And but he's self-reflexive and he's willing to talk about it. So it's a very telling exchange where he explains, do you mean Bharat Mata lives on this soil, this piece of land, that piece of land?

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:45.000
[Guest]: And he says, and then now he's reflecting, he says, well, it was kind of a wrong question.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:50.000
[Guest]: And that in their minds, Bharat Mata was a kind of a metaphorical thing.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:56.000
[Guest]: And when they said, you know, this particular soil is Bharat Mata, they didn't literally mean it.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:07.000
[Guest]: So what you see going on over here is a person who is encountering a subaltern culture that he doesn't quite understand.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:19.000
[Guest]: But then he still has to rationalize it. So in the end, the distance is kind of stitched up by his rationalization by saying, OK, yes, they have a different culture.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:24.000
[Guest]: It's not mine, but it makes sense in terms of how I think.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:32.000
[Guest]: So now Nehru is, you could say, the most farsighted of those liberal leaders, but still he's part of the elite.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:48.000
[Guest]: And in that encounter, you can see how the elite then takes on the kind of responsibility of working on behalf of the people who think in terms of Bharat Mata ki Jai

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:54.000
[Guest]: and think that this particular land is where Bharat Mata lives.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:22:00.000
[Guest]: But, you know, they are uneducated and they think that way. But I understand what they really mean.

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:11.000
[Guest]: So therefore, I can act on their behalf. So there is a kind of an appropriation of what the people think and a claim to represent them.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:16.000
[Guest]: Now, that's the most kind of a generous way you can think of this liberal elite.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:23.000
[Guest]: But in policy terms, then what ensues is that they would undertake various measures.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:30.000
[Guest]: And even if they didn't succeed, so, for example, land reform, you do half-hearted land reform.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:37.000
[Guest]: And when even land reform doesn't quite go to the extent that it should have in your own terms,

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:45.000
[Guest]: you can then rationalize it and say, well, given the political matrix, this is all we can accomplish at this time.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:49.000
[Guest]: But you've taken the responsibility of even determining that.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:55.000
[Guest]: So the whole agency in history then is appropriated by the elite.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:23:00.000
[Amit Varma]: And that condescension even plays out in ways which actually peak during the emergency.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:10.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, the family planning and the Naspandees and all that where you're making these life-changing decisions on behalf of the poor who you don't really give a damn about.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that even when the constitution was being framed, there were voices of dissent.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:20.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, Tajmul Hasan argued against the ability to suspend fundamental rights.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And H.V. Kamath, in fact, invoked the Weimar Constitution and the rise of Hitler and said that, no, we should not have similar provisions here.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And this was, of course, not Godwin's law because this was in the late 1940s. It's fresh in their minds.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:39.000
[Guest]: Yeah. I mean, one of the things in reading the constituent assembly debates,

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:51.000
[Guest]: I must say I was very impressed by the erudition, knowledge, and deep concern of its members.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:59.000
[Guest]: And also this kind of warning signs that they uttered at that time.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:06.000
[Guest]: So, yes, there were people who were aware that this could lead to something.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:20.000
[Guest]: And I think that's where the liberal elites believe that all this is necessary in a country like India with its vast mass of poverty and illiteracy.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:28.000
[Guest]: It places a certain demand on the elite to take responsibility.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:43.000
[Guest]: And also an expectation that it will remain so, that the country's leadership will be always guided by these kind of higher goals and more noble ideals of, you know, liberal leadership of the population.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:55.000
[Guest]: Now, if it had somehow happened that the liberal leadership was not torn by various kinds of caste and class and regional and linguistic conflicts

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:59.000
[Guest]: and had maintained that ideal, maybe things would have been different.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:04.000
[Guest]: But, you know, no law, no constitution is separate from society and politics.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:13.000
[Guest]: And so we can see down the line that belief and that expectation that this democracy would work,

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:26.000
[Guest]: or even if it's liberal led and elite led, because we would maintain this kind of a higher ideal, becomes a kind of a small minded, you know, politics.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:36.000
[Guest]: By the time you get to, I would say, particularly after Nehru's death, but it's visible even before, politics gets smaller and smaller.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:43.000
[Guest]: And the gap between the rhetoric and reality becomes wider and wider.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you do a great job of sort of juxtaposing the violence outside parliament in this ocean of turmoil that was around them.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And that island of calm inside where the framers are deliberating how exactly to frame the constitution.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:02.000
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, in their eyes, it makes sense to have a strong center.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:10.000
[Amit Varma]: But I'm just wondering that even despite this context, isn't there a sort of a will to power,

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:16.000
[Amit Varma]: which makes a state get stricken, try to increase its strength and its power at all times?

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:24.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, you know, you've mentioned that in 1950, the parliament as it then was passed the Preventive Detention Act.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And it was supposed to expire on April 1, 1951, which you call a cruel April Fool joke.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:34.000
[Amit Varma]: But year after year, this was renewed all the way till it became MISA in 1971.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And equally, there's, you know, one of my economist friends who's been on the show, Shruti Rajagopal,

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:44.000
[Amit Varma]: and she'd done a presentation, which I'll link from the page for this podcast, which is on YouTube,

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:50.000
[Amit Varma]: where she sort of traced out all the changes in the constitution since Nehru's times.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And people often have the impression that, oh, the real changes in the constitution happened when Indira came to power.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:02.000
[Amit Varma]: But the fact is that right from when Nehru took power, every time he felt it expedient to change the constitution,

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:05.000
[Amit Varma]: if it got in the way, he would simply amend the constitution.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:10.000
[Amit Varma]: And it was in fact joked about that the constitution is not a book, but a periodical.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:11.000
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:20.000
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, what we see the tendency over the last 71 years of our existence has been that the state is trying to always strongly centralize

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:26.000
[Amit Varma]: and increases power in any case, which we've even seen recently and throughout the 71 years.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:37.000
[Guest]: Yeah. You know, the expectation that, for example, Ambedkar had, that if you frame a constitution,

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:46.000
[Guest]: which gives state these extraordinary powers, but hem it with various kinds of rules and regulations,

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:52.000
[Guest]: somehow the state will not overreach. That was the kind of expectation.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:55.000
[Guest]: And that is why I think India has the longest constitution in the world,

00:27:55.000 --> 00:28:02.000
[Guest]: because somehow Ambedkar believed that if you had enough rules and regulations, you know, things would work.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:11.000
[Guest]: But of course, you know, that constitution operates in a real environment with real politics and real politicians who have real interests

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:17.000
[Guest]: and are grown by all sorts of different passions and interests.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:27.000
[Guest]: And so in practice, what happens is all those provisions which are expected to constrain you,

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:37.000
[Guest]: do not constrain you because the state is constantly, you know, gearing towards acquiring more and more power and exercising more and more power.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:44.000
[Guest]: And, you know, the temptation is something that no politician is able to resist.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:52.000
[Guest]: So even during, I mean, I find it ironic that, you know, one of the last things that the Charan Singh government does.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:56.000
[Guest]: Now, here is Charan Singh, who was put in jail by Indira Gandhi.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:05.000
[Guest]: And what does he do? One of the last things he does is to pass an ordinance reestablishing preventive detention.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:13.000
[Guest]: So, you know, one would have thought that for sheer political reasons, he would not do it.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:26.000
[Guest]: But I think once they are in the state, the temptation to exercise state power and expand state power is so great that very few politicians can resist it.

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:29.000
[Guest]: And it's not a moral failing as such.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:38.000
[Guest]: It's in a way systematic in the way our constitution has been framed and how it exists in our society.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And the nature of politics in the sense that if the like, I consider politics to be something that is morally corrosive.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:51.000
[Amit Varma]: To survive in it, you have to make the kind of compromises and do the kind of things that ensure that you have no principles at all.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:57.000
[Amit Varma]: So it's almost unfair to expect a politician who has got gotten to the top to actually be principled.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:02.000
[Amit Varma]: He will, you know, he's got there because of the lust for power and the drive for power and they'll do whatever.

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that you point out how, you know, Charan Singh, when he came to power, renewed the Preventive Detention Act.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:12.000
[Amit Varma]: I'd written a column two or three years ago comparing Modi to Indira Gandhi.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:21.000
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things I'm amused about was how Modi and Jaitley themselves had actually experienced the emergency in different ways.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And the assumption of this was that when they come to power, they'll sort of understand what the, how dangerous the power of the state can be.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:32.000
[Amit Varma]: And instead, it seems as if their mindset was, hamari baari aane do.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:42.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, that it doesn't matter who's in charge, even if they've suffered earlier from the, you know, even if they've been victims of state power.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:44.000
[Amit Varma]: Once they are in power, they're just going to expand the power of the state.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:56.000
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I think that, you know, in the run up to the emergency, it's the Allahabad court judgment that turns what was essentially a political conflict into a constitutional crisis.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:11.000
[Guest]: And that then makes then opposition leaders like, you know, Vajpayee, Advani, Jaitley, Modi and so on, into great advocates of liberal democracy.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:16.000
[Guest]: They didn't start out like that. They start out as Indira Hatao.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:17.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:24.000
[Guest]: That was the limited goal. But because of the emergency, they were suddenly turned into great advocates of liberal democracy.

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:33.000
[Guest]: And that wasn't going to last. So the moment they had achieved their purpose of, you know, Indira Hatao, then, you know, liberal democracy went out of window.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:40.000
[Guest]: Then, you know, it was back to more truncated version of what democracy means.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:44.000
[Amit Varma]: On that extremely depressing note, we'll take a commercial break. We'll be back in a minute.

