00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to The Scene and The Unseen. I'm chatting with Gyan Prakash, author of Emergency Chronicles.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:33:05.000
[Amit Varma]: Gyan, so before the break, we spoke about how sort of because of the imperatives of the violence around them, the Constituent Assembly framed a constitution that centralized state power

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:13.000
[Amit Varma]: and that had the means embedded within it to, you know, suspend fundamental rights that had, you know, and the parliament later came up with the Preventive Retention Act,

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:20.000
[Amit Varma]: which kept getting renewed all the way to Indira Gandhi. And that is sort of the political structural context of this.

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:32.000
[Amit Varma]: There's also a social context. And, you know, which you bring out very evocatively when you talk about, for example, all the students movements through the 50s and the 60s.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:41.000
[Amit Varma]: And there is this classic sort of hypocrisy that I find among the elites who ran our country is that while they themselves, when they were fighting against the British,

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:47.000
[Amit Varma]: they would all be for people rising up and so on. But the moment they were the state, they frowned upon it.

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, you've quoted Ambedkar in your book talking about how, you know, we used to use all of these methods of protest because we had to.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:00.000
[Amit Varma]: But now that there is a constitution and there's a constitutional republic, they are no longer valid.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, he called a lot of these protests starting from say, the 1955 Patna thing.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:08.000
[Amit Varma]: He was speaking before this, but he referred to it as the grammar of anarchy.

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And can you just sort of give me a backdrop of how over the years, you know, there were students protests, there was a jobs crisis,

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:25.000
[Amit Varma]: all of these things, much the same as they are today, in fact, and how that kind of set the scene for the 70s.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:33.000
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, many times when people look back to the early 50s and the early 60s,

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:38.000
[Guest]: they look at it kind of nostalgically, thinking that it was a time of consensus.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:49.000
[Guest]: In fact, right from the time of independence, various kinds of, you know, discontents and dissatisfactions and movements and uprisings,

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:58.000
[Guest]: they continue right through Nehru's death. They don't acquire the kind of scale that they do subsequently, but it's always there.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:11.000
[Guest]: But the fundamental problem is that the elites never saw the ordinary people as political subjects in their own right.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:19.000
[Guest]: And that is why the only conception that someone like Nehru has of Indians after 1947.

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:25.000
[Guest]: So what would be our, let's say, political agency? How would we be politically active?

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:30.000
[Guest]: Well, you should participate in the national effort towards development.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:34.000
[Guest]: So the state sets up, for example, let's say, you know, five year plan.

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:47.000
[Guest]: And in fact, one of my students has written on this. There was a concerted attempt to involve the population in making planning a part of kind of public consciousness.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:59.000
[Guest]: So the entire population should join in a kind of a national effort for, you know, grow more food, more planning and achieving all the kind of planning objectives.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:10.000
[Guest]: So even the activity that they imagined for the ordinary population was, in fact, mandated from above.

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:18.000
[Guest]: They just couldn't think of any kind of agency that would emerge from below on their own.

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:29.000
[Guest]: So that is why during, you know, the colonial rule, they could understand, you know, peasants and workers and students coming out on the streets against the British.

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:38.000
[Guest]: And they could be political subjects. But once we have independence, it's almost as if the need for political subjectivity disappears.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:45.000
[Guest]: And all they can now do is participate in the national effort, which is, of course, defined from above.

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:58.000
[Guest]: And so, you know, there is that moment in 1955 when Nehru goes to Patna and students are rioting and he addresses a meeting and he gets very angry.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:04.000
[Guest]: And he has this kind of bolster, masnad, and he throws into the crowd and says, this is not politics.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:13.000
[Guest]: This is gundaism, because any kind of agency that did not contribute to national effort for him was not real political agency.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And the irony is mind blowing because the British could have said the same thing to Gandhi and him.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Exactly, exactly.

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And the picture you paint of what's happening in the 50s is sounded, you know, I often forget being middle aged myself that 60% of India is born after liberalization, after 91.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of the history behind them is sort of something for the books.

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:43.000
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, if you actually think about it, there are so many parallels of those times with current times, like when you were speaking about the India against corruption movement of 2011.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:48.000
[Amit Varma]: And there are so many parallels with what was happening earlier in the 1960s.

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:52.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, there was a jobs crisis and we're going to have a far bigger jobs crisis now.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's already happening.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:56.000
[Amit Varma]: There are these youth agitations.

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:00.000
[Amit Varma]: There are these different movements popping up which have different responses to the different crisis.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:09.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, you know, Thackeray's populist movements, you know, starts in the late 60s, where he's like Bombay for Bombayites and Bombay for Maharashtrians.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:13.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, and at that time, of course, his ire is against the South Indians.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:17.000
[Amit Varma]: But later through the decades, it, you know, finds various different targets.

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:22.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's almost an exact analog of what is happening at a sort of a national scale today.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:30.000
[Amit Varma]: And you have those, that same kind of ferment is taking place through all the student politics of the 60s and so on.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And you also talk of how parallelly at the same time, as a party, the Congress is disintegrating and the system is also suffering.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Even as the administrative structure becomes bigger and, you know, gets into almost a kind of sclerotic mode.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:52.000
[Amit Varma]: You have the Congress party going through its own sort of turmoil and all these different strands leading to 1975.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:39:02.000
[Guest]: Yeah. And, you know, when I was looking at the politics in the 60s, one thing I was struck by was that, you know,

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:11.000
[Guest]: most accounts of emergency, which even look at, you know, the JP movement, imagine it to be a completely uniquely Indian phenomenon.

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:18.000
[Guest]: So I wanted to expand the canvas and say, well, this is part of a kind of a global 1968.

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:29.000
[Guest]: And across the world, you have a certain discontent with the postwar regimes that had come into being across the world.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:39.000
[Guest]: So cultural revolution in China, Prague Spring in Czechoslovakia, anti-Vietnam War movement, counterculture movement, May 68.

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:50.000
[Guest]: And what unites all of them, they all have very specific causes, but what unites all of them is kind of an anti-establishment thinking.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:40:02.000
[Guest]: And the idea that, you know, established institutions and established ways of representing your voices have failed and that they have to look for something new.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:11.000
[Guest]: And India also, similar kind of thing is happening. So the Shiv Sena, whatever we might think of its ideology,

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:17.000
[Guest]: but the idea that, you know, politics lies on the street and we have to occupy the street.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:23.000
[Guest]: Anti-Hindi agitation in the South. And then, of course, Naxalism.

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:33.000
[Guest]: So all of them represent a challenge, which is somewhat different from the challenges that had come up earlier,

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:42.000
[Guest]: in that they are now questioning the institutional framework that Indian democracy had worked out

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:47.000
[Guest]: and the ability of that institutional framework to deliver the goods.

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:59.000
[Guest]: So that really creates this kind of crisis through the 60s. And of course, the Congress, as a response to the social change that is happening,

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:08.000
[Guest]: in part also caused by some of the changes that the government itself had introduced, like limited land reform.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:19.000
[Guest]: So you have for the first time the emergence of backward caste in North India. I mean, it was already there in the South, but in North India.

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:26.000
[Guest]: And I think, you know, you have to give credit to Indira Gandhi's sort of political astuteness,

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:39.000
[Guest]: that she recognized that the Congress was no longer able to command loyalty the way it had previously through its kind of patron-client system.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:47.000
[Guest]: So when the Congress is defeated for the first time in the assembly elections in nine states in 1967,

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:51.000
[Guest]: she realizes that something needs to be done.

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:58.000
[Guest]: You know, people see it largely in terms of factionalism, that she is trying to, you know, gather her power.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:03.000
[Guest]: But, you know, the two needn't be contradictory. I mean, she was trying to do that,

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:08.000
[Guest]: but she also recognized that, you know, the old ways will not work.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:16.000
[Guest]: And so when she splits the party in 1969, she's in fact responding to this recognition that things are changing,

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:22.000
[Guest]: the Congress itself is changing, and that Congress cannot be a ruling party in the old way.

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:32.000
[Guest]: And it has to, you know, rejuvenate itself by adopting a more, you know, left-wing ideology.

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:40.000
[Guest]: So, and I think that is kind of a symptom of the change that's going on in the country.

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:46.000
[Amit Varma]: And sort of go back to the parallels in, I want to ask you about JP. So to sort of come to that, you know,

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:50.000
[Amit Varma]: recently I read Mayank Gandhi's book about how the Aam Aadmi Party was formed.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And he describes in detail how they sort of how he was chatting with Arvind Kejriwal and they decided that,

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:01.000
[Amit Varma]: okay, we need a figurehead who will have that kind of resonance with the masses.

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:06.000
[Amit Varma]: And then they decide upon Anna Hazare and they get him and it works for a period of time.

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:11.000
[Amit Varma]: But JP, on the other hand, was almost a model for that.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:19.000
[Amit Varma]: But JP was also a leader of tremendous stature, someone who was friends with Jawahar and Kamla,

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:25.000
[Amit Varma]: who, you know, almost had this sort of uncle-niece affection for Indira,

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:28.000
[Amit Varma]: who was disillusioned from politics for many years after this thing.

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:35.000
[Amit Varma]: But he comes up as a sort of a natural focal point of the movements that are building up in the early 70s,

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:39.000
[Amit Varma]: especially the student movements in Bihar. And all the moment he becomes a face of that,

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:43.000
[Amit Varma]: it becomes something enormous that can challenge Indira Gandhi.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Now, I mean, what do you think of Kalay's great man theory of history?

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:53.000
[Amit Varma]: And do you think if JP had not existed, things would nevertheless have played out the same or, you know?

00:43:53.000 --> 00:44:00.000
[Guest]: No, I mean, I think it's not surprising that, you know, they found JP. I mean, JP didn't find them.

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:08.000
[Guest]: And, you know, there is a, this is something to think about that, you know, even now, in the, across the world,

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:14.000
[Guest]: if you think of the young people in Britain who flocked the Labour Party,

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:20.000
[Guest]: and who do they make their leader? Jeremy Corbyn. Certainly not a young person.

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:22.000
[Guest]: The young people in the US.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:23.000
[Guest]: Yeah, Bernie Sanders.

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:33.000
[Guest]: And same way over here. I mean, I think it has something to do with the fact that the young people were expressing

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:43.000
[Guest]: no faith in the existing political system. And, you know, in both Nav Nirman movement in Gujarat and

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:51.000
[Guest]: Chhatra Yuva committee in Bihar, there were political parties which were, you know, trying to capture them, you know,

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:57.000
[Guest]: Jan Sangh at that time was very active and, you know, ABVP, they were trying to capture them.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:04.000
[Guest]: But they realized that they needed someone other than a straight political personality to lead this movement.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:12.000
[Guest]: Because the movement's urge was to, you know, break free from the existing political setup.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:20.000
[Guest]: And it's not surprising then that they found a leader who had retired from formal politics, JP.

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:27.000
[Guest]: And who also had this saintly image that a person who doesn't seek political office for himself,

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:32.000
[Guest]: and therefore he's not leading the movement against Indira Gandhi because he wants to get into power.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:37.000
[Guest]: Whereas all the opposition parties, you know, couldn't escape that charge.

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:44.000
[Guest]: So, I mean, I think it's just fitting that they would have found someone like JP.

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:46.000
[Guest]: But had they not found him?

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:51.000
[Guest]: Then they might have, you know, thrown up a leadership within their own ranks.

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:57.000
[Guest]: But, you know, they wouldn't have acquired that kind of a national presence.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:04.000
[Guest]: So they did throw up, you know, that's the time when Lalu and Nitish both come up in Bihar.

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:09.000
[Guest]: In fact, you know, if you look at the political map today, many of those people,

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:13.000
[Guest]: they all came up into political prominence in the 70s.

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:17.000
[Amit Varma]: JP was in student politics, Modi was a worker for the BJP.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:22.000
[Guest]: Ravi Shankar Prasad, all these people, you know, they all came up during that time.

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. And the other fascinating character during this time is Sanjay Gandhi.

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:34.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, we are recording this on 17 December and just a couple of days back,

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:37.000
[Amit Varma]: he had his, I think, birth anniversary.

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:42.000
[Amit Varma]: And the Congress Party put out a tweet celebrating him as a visionary leader and someone who cared for the poor.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Did you see that? What did you think about that?

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:56.000
[Guest]: No, you know, in writing about Sanjay Gandhi, one of the problems was that the man really didn't leave a diary or a substantial body of writing.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:01.000
[Guest]: So it was hard to figure out what he stood for.

00:47:01.000 --> 00:47:06.000
[Guest]: So all I had going for it was really his actions.

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:11.000
[Guest]: And Indira often said about Sanjay that, you know, he's a man of action. He's not a man of ideas.

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:20.000
[Guest]: So, you know, this latter day revisionism, I think, you know, the Congress has to at some point come clean.

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:27.000
[Guest]: If it has to have any kind of credible future as a national alternative.

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:34.000
[Guest]: You can't keep saying, well, you know, certain things went wrong, but, you know, he was great.

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:41.000
[Guest]: So I don't know if Sanjay Gandhi will be fully rehabilitated because the memories of people are horrendous.

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:50.000
[Guest]: Yeah. So I know now people credit him with Maruti, you know.

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:58.000
[Guest]: But that's a different story. I mean, I don't think he can be directly credited, although he played a role and he played an indirect role.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:04.000
[Guest]: He wasn't aware of what he was up to. But if you see it in the kind of a larger picture,

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:13.000
[Guest]: his Maruti was the wedge to pry open the control economy.

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:17.000
[Guest]: So it happened through crony capitalism. That's the irony of it.

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:25.000
[Guest]: So it's not because, you know, lots of people thought that, you know, on their study or on their rational judgment,

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:30.000
[Guest]: that we should break free from License Raj and move to something else.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:33.000
[Guest]: Just so happened, you know, he was Prime Minister's son.

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:37.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it seems to me more than an attempt to open up the markets.

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:44.000
[Amit Varma]: It seems to me a classic case of cronyism where state power is essentially used to push one man's interest.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:49.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's very anti-competitive. For example, the way he gets an industrial license in 69,

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:53.000
[Amit Varma]: which you describe where established companies haven't been able to get that.

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that and also resonant that you describe Sanjay's mechanical mindset,

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:02.000
[Amit Varma]: what today people call the engineering mindset. Right.

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And in that sense, he almost seems to be a caricature of what the state was,

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:12.000
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that he had this engineering mindset, a top-down vision of the world.

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Everything has to be planned. Coercion is essential to what he wants to do.

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:21.000
[Amit Varma]: And of course, when it comes to his private endeavors like Maruti, he fails completely.

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:29.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the Washington Post in 74, you've quoted them as describing his car as an inadvertent way of population control.

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Because it was such an incompetent piece of machinery.

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:39.000
[Amit Varma]: But then once he has state power at his disposal, he uses that for things like slum clearing,

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:42.000
[Amit Varma]: like in the Turkmen Gate where you have a chapter which is, you know,

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:47.000
[Amit Varma]: very powerfully describes that and all the family planning nonsense that he did.

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And while it seems that, okay, here is a man who is clearly a moral monster,

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:57.000
[Amit Varma]: but at the same time, everything that he is doing or whatever we can make out from about his beliefs,

00:49:57.000 --> 00:50:01.000
[Amit Varma]: from his actions, epitomize what the Indian state has always been.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:08.000
[Guest]: Yeah. You know, let me just step back from both sterilization and Maruti,

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:15.000
[Guest]: but I want to come back to it in a more roundabout way, in the sense that when we think of the emergency

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:21.000
[Guest]: and when we think of the memory of sterilization or Maruti or slum clearance,

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:27.000
[Guest]: they seem to epitomize the tyranny of emergency.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:33.000
[Guest]: And in that sense, they become our understanding of emergency.

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:37.000
[Guest]: And of course, you know, they were tyrannical and, you know,

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:41.000
[Guest]: I don't want to minimize the oppression that they accomplished.

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:47.000
[Guest]: But if you want to understand the emergency, not only in negative terms,

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:56.000
[Guest]: and by which I mean emergency just as suppression of rights, denial of press freedom, censorship.

00:50:56.000 --> 00:51:04.000
[Guest]: But if you want to ask what was emergency as a form of rule and as a vision of governance

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:12.000
[Guest]: or as a vision of society, then you can think of sterilization and slum clearance

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:20.000
[Guest]: as two kind of classic examples of how elite thought India should function.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:28.000
[Guest]: And so in one case, the idea is that the number of the poor is growing too much.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:33.000
[Guest]: So population growth is a problem, but it's particularly a problem because the wrong kind of people

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:45.000
[Guest]: are growing. And the second is against the poor and that the poor are spoiling your urban beautification

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:53.000
[Guest]: by living in slums and creating slums. So the idea is to tackle poverty through population control

00:51:53.000 --> 00:52:00.000
[Guest]: and through slum clearance. So you can say that that's the positive vision of the emergency.

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:03.000
[Guest]: Positive, not in the sense that it's good.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:04.000
[Amit Varma]: This is what they want to do.

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:09.000
[Guest]: Yeah, but this is what they want to do. And but then you need to step back and ask,

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:15.000
[Guest]: so where does this come from? You know, again, Sanjay Gandhi is, of course, critical in all of this.

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:23.000
[Guest]: But one of the things that I found really revealing even to me was that although in my mind also,

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:27.000
[Guest]: you know, I associated Sanjay Gandhi with sterilization and urban clearance.

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:34.000
[Guest]: And when I started looking into its history, I found that, in fact, it goes back to the 1950s.

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:42.000
[Guest]: And it's really part of a global movement. And the interesting thing about the population control activists,

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:48.000
[Guest]: most of them, you know, situated in the United States and in Europe, but mainly in the United States,

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:55.000
[Guest]: they are demographers and they are worried about population growth and again,

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:59.000
[Guest]: the wrong kind of population growth. And of course, India is at the center of this.

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:06.000
[Guest]: So all these population activists begin their programs, you know, setting up demography training,

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:13.000
[Guest]: various population control programs in India in the 50s and really gets going by the end of the 50s and early 60s.

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:20.000
[Guest]: So by the time Sanjay Gandhi comes along, that program has been in existence, encouraged,

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:29.000
[Guest]: financed by the Ford Foundation. And, you know, I read accounts about how the family planning ministry

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:37.000
[Guest]: was overrun by these consultants financed by the Ford Foundation and, you know, who were kind of running the show.

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:43.000
[Guest]: So by the time, you know, Sanjay Gandhi comes along, the program is well established.

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:50.000
[Guest]: There are, you know, population control zealots in Indian ministry, Indian government, you know,

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:54.000
[Guest]: including Ashoka Mehta, who was, you know, family planning minister.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:59.000
[Guest]: And, you know, he says, we have to take up this issue on a war footing.

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:06.000
[Guest]: So the war metaphor and, you know, coercion, they were already instituted into the system.

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:14.000
[Guest]: What Sanjay Gandhi does is to really ratchet this up several notches, and it becomes far more coercive.

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:19.000
[Guest]: And the same thing happens with slum clearance as well.

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:26.000
[Guest]: And, you know, there's an interesting statement by Jagmohan, who was then the vice chairman of DDA,

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:32.000
[Guest]: and who says, you know, he sees it as part of, you know, urban planning and part of Delhi Master Plan.

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:40.000
[Guest]: And he says, you know, we needed the sign to come, you know, give it sort of kickstart the process.

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:48.000
[Guest]: So again, you know, you see these as part of, you know, long term history of post independence India,

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:56.000
[Guest]: which, you know, acquires a certain direction during the emergency, but it doesn't, emergency doesn't invent it.

00:54:56.000 --> 00:55:00.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's, you know, speaking of Jagmohan, there's another telling quote in your book where you talk about

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:07.000
[Amit Varma]: how Jagmohan, when Turkmen Gate was happening, he justified it by saying, we didn't leave Pakistan to create another Pakistan.

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. You know, and that same kind of thinking, you could say, permeates today, where, you know,

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:18.000
[Amit Varma]: the ban on cow slaughter, for example, is basically an attack on one community.

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:22.000
[Amit Varma]: It's, you know, the whole cow thing is just a proxy for that.

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:27.000
[Amit Varma]: And just speaking of population planning, I mean, obviously, and this is something I've written a lot about in the past,

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:34.000
[Amit Varma]: because I've always sort of thought of people as the ultimate resource as the economist Julian Simon puts it,

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:42.000
[Amit Varma]: that our population is actually a strength and not a weakness, because it's a positive game and people are the greatest resource.

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:49.000
[Amit Varma]: And the US was dominated by this sort of Malthusian thinking in the 40s, 50s, 60s.

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:55.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, Paul Ehrlich, who was one of the biggest doomsayers, would write books about how we were heading for a crisis.

00:55:55.000 --> 00:56:02.000
[Amit Varma]: I think in 1969, he or one of his fellows predicted that there would be famines in the US by 75.

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:07.000
[Amit Varma]: And that the poor country should be allowed to starve because there is a scarcity of resources.

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And all this, of course, is complete nonsense. And I'll put links to the pieces I've written on the page for this episode.

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Moving on from Sanjay and I really, people who haven't read about the emergency before,

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:25.000
[Amit Varma]: I strongly recommend them to read your book and other books on it,

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:31.000
[Amit Varma]: because the kind of horrors that were inflicted by Sanjay Gandhi and Indira Gandhi are just mind numbing.

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:34.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting how they've almost become benign figures today.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:40.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, I've heard people defend the things they did and speak about Indira Gandhi's monumental achievements.

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:46.000
[Amit Varma]: And of course, on many more grounds than just the emergency, she damaged India enormously.

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:53.000
[Amit Varma]: One of the delightful things I found about your book is that it also shows your immersion into the culture of the time.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:57:02.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, you talk about Shamban Eagle's Ankur and Nishant as films that sort of give a picture of what society at the time was like.

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:05.000
[Amit Varma]: You quote from Nirala, I think, if I'm not mistaken.

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:12.000
[Amit Varma]: You write about Nirmal Varma's novel at the end of the emergency, which is so evocative.

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:18.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit more about that. Like when you were researching the book, did you also consciously make an effort to sort of see?

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:24.000
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, I'll tell you two stories about this. One is that when I started thinking about writing this book,

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:30.000
[Guest]: I didn't want to write a straight political history, you know, and I'm not particularly interested in it.

00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:37.000
[Guest]: And I just didn't want to write about Indira Gandhi or Sanjay Gandhi and Murarji and so on. That was not.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:50.000
[Guest]: So I was looking for a different form. And it just so happened that during that time, I read this British detective fiction writer, Philip Kerr.

00:57:50.000 --> 00:58:03.000
[Guest]: And he has this trilogy called Berlin Noir. The first one is set in 1933, second in 1934, and the third in 1947.

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:12.000
[Guest]: And you have a private eye, Philip Gunther, you know, who examines usual private eye cases, you know, divorce, missing person.

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:19.000
[Guest]: But the interesting thing what he does is that as Bernie Gunther is examining these cases,

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:24.000
[Guest]: he runs up first against the Nazis coming to power, then they are in power.

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:32.000
[Guest]: And the third one, which is my favorite, 47 post-war Berlin, where Americans, the Brits, the Russians,

00:58:32.000 --> 00:58:35.000
[Guest]: they're all jockeying for influence. And Bernie is still following those cases.

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:41.000
[Guest]: And you get a kind of portrait of that Berlin through his examination.

00:58:41.000 --> 00:58:52.000
[Guest]: So I was, when I first started thinking about writing this, I sort of knew about this case, but hadn't paid much attention to it.

00:58:52.000 --> 00:59:00.000
[Guest]: And that was the case of Prabir Purukast who was kidnapped in JNU in 1975 by PSB.

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:03.000
[Amit Varma]: One of the parallel JNUs in the center of the action.

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:14.000
[Guest]: Right. So I thought, well, you know, that story, I can, instead of Bernie Gunther, I would be the detective and I would be, you know, looking at clues.

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:20.000
[Guest]: So how does an ordinary student get abducted?

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:26.000
[Guest]: A big explanation is the emergency, but then the emergency itself has to be explained.

00:59:26.000 --> 00:59:31.000
[Guest]: But he's arrested under MISA. And so why do we have laws like that? And what is the history of it?

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:44.000
[Guest]: So I thought that if I could keep his story as the kind of anchor of the book and each of the chapters would, in a way, take one element of that story.

00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:49.000
[Guest]: So I thought that's the kind of form that the book would take.

00:59:49.000 --> 01:00:01.000
[Guest]: So that's what I tried to do. And the second was, as I said, you know, I didn't want to write straight political history because also I didn't think that that would really capture what I wanted to capture,

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:16.000
[Guest]: which is, for example, if you want to show the kind of environment in which first the student youth movement took place and then the emergency was declared,

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:25.000
[Guest]: you cannot do it only through a political narrative and that you have to cast your net wider and see how it was being culturally represented.

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:32.000
[Guest]: Because one of the things that, you know, was very clear was that it's a very angry period.

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:40.000
[Guest]: There's a lot of anger on the street, you know, starting with, for example, the Shiv Sena in Bombay, you know, it's politics of anger.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:46.000
[Guest]: And even when the students and youth, they come out in the streets, there's a lot of brickbatting, you know, battles with the police.

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:51.000
[Guest]: And so how do you catch the kind of emotional mood of the country at that time?

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:58.000
[Guest]: And I thought for that, you know, both literature and cinema are very good medium.

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:07.000
[Guest]: And of course, I remembered Benegal's films from having seen it before, but hadn't quite seen them in this context.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:18.000
[Guest]: And when I was, you know, reading around it and saw the films again, then I thought, why didn't I see it this way before?

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:29.000
[Guest]: You know, because they're so clearly of that moment and express all the kind of frustrations and anger and also a sense of, you know, impasse.

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:40.000
[Guest]: Particularly, you know, in this, not in Angkor, well, Angkor also, you know, the last moment in the film where little boy throws stone.

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:47.000
[Guest]: On the one hand, it's a kind of a hopeful sign that, you know, of rebellion, but also its ineffectiveness.

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:51.000
[Guest]: So I thought, well, these were, you know, really part of the story.

01:01:51.000 --> 01:02:01.000
[Guest]: And even among sort of literary writings, of course, everyone knew of ruined and mysteries of fine balance, you know, which I also admire greatly.

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:05.000
[Guest]: But it was a well-known thing and it was written much later.

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:09.000
[Guest]: So I wanted to find that something that was written in that moment.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:15.000
[Guest]: And that's where I found both Nirmal Verma and Rahim Asum Raza, you know.

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:27.000
[Guest]: What I found very interesting about Rahim Asum Raza's novel is that it's a novel in which the character addresses the reader directly, almost as a kind of a political speech, you know.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:31.000
[Guest]: So it carries that kind of immediacy of the moment.

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:47.000
[Guest]: As a novel, it's not so great, but I found it as a piece of writing and as a kind of a literary commentary and the urge in the writer to represent everything that's going on during the emergency very, very telling.

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:56.000
[Guest]: So I wanted to, you know, really bring both literature and cinema in order to capture something of the kind of a cultural and political.

01:02:56.000 --> 01:03:01.000
[Guest]: And I thought even the political mood cannot be captured without its culture, you know.

01:03:01.000 --> 01:03:03.000
[Amit Varma]: No, and I found its structure very fascinating.

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Like I read this book on cognitive neuroscience recently called Behave by Robert Sapolsky, where he basically takes actions and then he examines them one level at a time.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:23.000
[Amit Varma]: So the immediate proximate things which led to the action and then what is happening at the level of the brain and then what happened before that at the level of evolution and so on going all the way back.

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:36.000
[Amit Varma]: And how you just described the structure of this book even seems like you're taking that Praveep Purkaya's case and then you're doing a sort of a forensic investigation of it where the most proximate causes it's a case of mistaken identity.

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:42.000
[Amit Varma]: And then you go one level above that and it's the emergency and then you go another level above that and you go back to the Constitution.

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:48.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, that's extremely fascinating and a very interesting way of approaching a book of history.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:53.000
[Amit Varma]: Where I'd like to sort of end this episode by is two questions really.

01:03:53.000 --> 01:04:01.000
[Amit Varma]: One, what are the sort of parallels you see between that period, the ferment of the emergency and between what is happening?

01:04:01.000 --> 01:04:08.000
[Guest]: Yeah, well, you know, I was writing this book actually here, sitting here in Mumbai in 2016-17.

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:13.000
[Guest]: And it was the kind of a stereophonic experience.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:20.000
[Guest]: It was, you know, Modi here and Trump there. And so I was kind of thinking of both.

01:04:20.000 --> 01:04:29.000
[Guest]: And it seemed to me that, you know, around that time and even now, you know, people were talking about undeclared emergency.

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:42.000
[Guest]: And I thought, in fact, you know, there were those kinds of parallels, the kind of stature in political power and authority that Narendra Modi had acquired was very similar to Indira Gandhi.

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:57.000
[Guest]: And even greater. But what I found really striking and that I don't think is captured by the term undeclared emergency is that there are many new elements in play now.

01:04:57.000 --> 01:05:03.000
[Guest]: So, you know, the media landscape has changed completely from the time of Indira Gandhi.

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:08.000
[Guest]: Private media. Indira Gandhi didn't have Arnab Goswami.

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:13.000
[Guest]: She didn't have a WhatsApp army. Yeah, we didn't have social media.

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:21.000
[Guest]: Indira Gandhi didn't have the kind of foot soldiers that Modi has with, you know, the cow vigilantes and lynchings and so on.

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:34.000
[Guest]: So he's got actually people on the street. As also in the digital sphere with, you know, a number of, you know, BJP trolls and so on.

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:45.000
[Guest]: So. And I find that that kind of power is far more ominous and dangerous and enduring than the kind of power that Indira Gandhi had.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:56.000
[Guest]: And so, in fact, you could argue that it was precisely the lack of that kind of popular power that forced her to resort to the emergency.

01:05:56.000 --> 01:06:06.000
[Guest]: Whereas Narendra Modi enjoys power at that level, you know, in the media and on the street.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:19.000
[Guest]: And plus, you know, given what I've written about the enduring power of the state, he can just utilize those part of the state and he doesn't have to formally declare emergency.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:27.000
[Guest]: And so you get a form of kind of authority and power, you know, a lot of people use the F word, you know, the fascism.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:37.000
[Guest]: That's a kind of real possibility here because of this kind of support on the street that he can have the gangs, you know, attack people and so on.

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:42.000
[Amit Varma]: And there's actually a stunning irony there because you describe in your book that, you know,

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:51.000
[Amit Varma]: one of the reasons JP had to sort of compromise with the Jansang and make them part of the movement was he needed their foot soldiers to oppose Indira Gandhi.

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:58.000
[Amit Varma]: And now suddenly those same foot soldiers are essentially on the other side as an adjunct to state power instead of opposing it.

01:06:58.000 --> 01:07:03.000
[Guest]: Exactly. Yeah. So, you know, the parallel over there, they're striking.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:12.000
[Guest]: And as I said, you know, I think they are even more ominous than Indira Gandhi.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:22.000
[Guest]: And, you know, sometimes I wonder that, you know, if the Allahabad judgment hadn't taken place, which, you know, put her kind of legal position in jeopardy,

01:07:22.000 --> 01:07:35.000
[Guest]: she might not have declared the emergency and she might have just used the ordinary, you know, state powers to, you know, control the population and maintain herself in power.

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:41.000
[Guest]: Then, you know, then we wouldn't be speaking about, oh, my goodness, that emergency, that horrible thing that happened.

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:48.000
[Guest]: It would be normalized. It would be normalized, you know, but it was the Allahabad judgment that really turned into something else.

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:58.000
[Guest]: If, you know, Modi doesn't have an Allahabad judgment to, you know, deal with, he can, you know, continue, you know, keep building in power.

01:07:58.000 --> 01:08:11.000
[Guest]: And I just find that, you know, that kind of power that he enjoys also produces a kind of hubris that is really quite stunning.

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:21.000
[Guest]: I was just reading, you know, today's newspaper that, you know, right after a defeat in midterm election, the arrogance of power is just quite stunning.

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:33.000
[Guest]: And, you know, you expect the prime minister, once you acquire that position, to adopt a somewhat sort of statesman like tone.

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:42.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, here it's, I mean, to your islands analogy again, they become islands of arrogance, insulated from sort of reality.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:55.000
[Amit Varma]: My other question, which actually disturbs me when I think about it is that, you know, as you've sort of correctly pointed out that, you know, our constitution was framed by and our state was shaped by a liberal elite, which was sort of out of touch with society.

01:08:55.000 --> 01:08:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And at that time, society didn't really have a voice.

01:08:57.000 --> 01:09:08.000
[Amit Varma]: They could be in the villages and do Bharat Mata Ki Jaya or whatever, as in Nehru's anecdote. But today, in some senses, it seems that society has actually caught up and is asserting itself.

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:21.000
[Amit Varma]: And it is not the liberal society that our constitution envisaged. You know, I would in fact say, for example, that one seminal moment in all of this is, and I wrote a column in the Times of India about this negative one.

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:33.000
[Amit Varma]: I don't know if you'd agree with its premise, but is that Adityanath's coming to power in UP is actually a moment where society has caught up with the state, where it's kind of asserting itself and saying, this is what we are.

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:44.000
[Amit Varma]: You liberal elites can stuff your constitution. This is what we are. And that also then brings upon the moral dilemma of what do you now do?

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Should a state be the reflection of society? And if this is what society is, where are we and how are we? We are also in a sense like Nehru liberal elites.

01:09:55.000 --> 01:10:02.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm a very different kind of liberal, I'd say, but nevertheless, we are elites. How are we to think about this?

01:10:02.000 --> 01:10:18.000
[Guest]: Well, you know, I don't think the genie can be put back in the bottle. And I don't think that it's particularly productive to think of the present in terms of what it lacks and what we have lost.

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:35.000
[Guest]: That world is gone. Democracy has acquired a new shape. And so we have to think of how can we practice democracy to realize its kind of ideals.

01:10:35.000 --> 01:10:49.000
[Guest]: And it's really, when you kind of distill it down to its essence, the promise of democracy is self-rule, self-rule and equality, that we are all equal.

01:10:49.000 --> 01:11:01.000
[Guest]: So we have to think of some different institutional mechanisms, different kinds of ideologies in order to bring that into being.

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:11.000
[Guest]: A phenomenon like, you know, Yogi Adityanath and so on, I would slightly disagree over there and say, well, he's not society.

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:18.000
[Guest]: He's one expression of society and that there are other expressions of society.

01:11:18.000 --> 01:11:28.000
[Guest]: So in general, I would say, yes, you know, there has to be a way in which society is more fully present in the affairs of the state.

01:11:28.000 --> 01:11:35.000
[Guest]: But that determination of what that society is, is itself a kind of a political and democratic process.

01:11:35.000 --> 01:11:48.000
[Guest]: And now what's happening with Adityanath is that Adityanath is, you know, resorting to the same old kind of state power to impose his vision of society.

01:11:48.000 --> 01:12:02.000
[Guest]: So we have to, in a way, I would say the democratic procedure would be to oppose that notion and come up with an alternative vision of society and work towards its fuller expression in the state.

01:12:02.000 --> 01:12:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, would you disagree with Ambedkar's pessimism and say that perhaps society can be changed from inside, that it doesn't need state coercion for it to be changed from the top?

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:23.000
[Guest]: Absolutely. I mean, I think, you know, any kind of enduring social change has to come from within and has to be generated from below.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:34.000
[Guest]: So in that sense, you know, I mean, I don't think of just gloom and doom because, you know, like Black Lives Matter and, you know, and Dalit movement here.

01:12:34.000 --> 01:12:44.000
[Guest]: I mean, there are, these are kind of signs of, you know, positive change where you may not agree with the whole range of things, but, you know, change comes in form.

01:12:44.000 --> 01:12:50.000
[Guest]: Some you like, some you don't like, but, you know, they are in the kind of a right direction.

01:12:50.000 --> 01:13:01.000
[Guest]: So and I think, you know, the movement for democracy from those kinds of perspectives is something to be, you know, welcome.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:04.000
[Amit Varma]: On that positive note, thank you so much, Gyan, for coming on the show.

01:13:04.000 --> 01:13:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Thank you for it was enjoyable.

01:13:34.000 --> 01:13:59.000
